```

In this example, we first define the sectioning commands using the `\section`, `\subsection`, etc. commands. These commands are the building blocks of the table of contents, as they indicate the structure of the document.

After the content, we use the `\tableofcontents` command, which LaTeX automatically generates based on the sectioning commands used in the document. This command will produce a list of all section and subsection titles, with links to the corresponding pages.

Remember to include this command after all your sections and subsections have been defined, but before the actual content of the document.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX using FEN notation, you can use the `tikz` package, which provides a powerful tool for drawing diagrams and graphs. Here's a step-by-step guide and the code to create a chessboard with the given FEN notation:

1. First, make sure you have the `tikz` package installed. If not, add it to your LaTeX document by including the following line in the preamble:
```latex
\usepackage{tikz}
```

2. Define a new command to draw a single chess square. You can use the ` tikzpicture`, `node`, and `rectangle` commands. Here's an example for a 8x8 board:
```latex
\newcommand{\chessSquare}[2]{
    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.4]
        \node[fill=white, draw=black, minimum size=1cm] (square) at (#1, #2) {};
        \node at (#1-0.2, #2-0.2) {$1$};
        \node at (#1+0.2, #2-0.2) {$2$};
        \node at (#1-0.2, #2+0.2) {$3$};
        \node at (#1+0.2, #2+0.2) {$4$};
        \node at (#1-0.5, #2) {$5$};
        \node at (#1+0.5, #2) {$6$};
        \node at (#1, #2-0.5) {$7$};
        \node at (#1, #2+0.5) {$8$};
    \end{tikzpicture}
}
```
3. Now, parse the FEN notation to create a list of square coordinates and their contents (white or black). For example, a typical FEN notation might look like this: `r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1`. Replace `r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1` with the actual FEN you want to represent.

4. Create a loop to draw each square based on the FEN coordinates and content. You can use the `foreach` loop from the `pgf` package:
```latex
\usepackage{pgf}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
    \foreach \x in {0, 1, ..., 7} {
        \foreach \y in {0, 1, ..., 7} {
            \ifcase\y
                \or \chessSquare{\x*8-0.5}{\y*8-0.5}{} % White square
                \or \chessSquare{\x*8+0.5}{\y*8-0.5}{} % Black square
            \fi
        }
    }
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```
